An empty cell is actually populated with `' '` and the default colour:

```rust
impl Default for Cell {
    fn default() -> Cell {
        Cell::new(
            ' ',
            Color::Named(NamedColor::Foreground),
            Color::Named(NamedColor::Background)
        )
    }
}
```

So the problem I guess is that white space characters ('\n', '\t', ...)don't update the relevant cells with a colour update

@CarwynNelson 

I think the modification would need to be where the white space characters are handled.
First let's start with '\n' in `src/term/mod.rs`:

```rust
    fn linefeed(&mut self) {
        debug_println!("linefeed");
        if self.cursor.line + 1 == self.scroll_region.end {
            self.scroll_up(Line(1));
        } else {
            self.cursor.line += 1;
        }
    }
```

This should update the current line and add colour data to the cells that need it. I'll see if I can implement that

Just looking at where `linefeed` is used in `Impl ansi::Handler for Term` and it seems that it should only be called when scrolling past the end of the scroll region?

```rust
if (self.cursor.line + 1) >= self.scroll_region.end {
    self.linefeed();
} else {
    self.cursor.line += 1;
}
```

Of course looking at the debug log shows `linefeed` being called when I simply move the (vim) cursor down one line. I'm guessing I'm not understanding this correctly. Could somebody explain to me what is actually going on in this part of the code?

EDIT: Here i'm assuming the `scroll_region.end` is the end of everything that should be visible on screen. In other words I was guessing that this code is to do with shifting the view up so that the line out of view can be rendered. If that makes any sort of sense.
